{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492664","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492664"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:40:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1123"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1123"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.1,0.1,0.14,0.19]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90775"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1123","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1123"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1123"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74874"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"645"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"2147"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"31115"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90775","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90775"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 31-year-old prison inmate is brought to the Emergency Department after swallowing a razor blade. He tells the medical staff that he swallowed the blade about 12 hours earlier. He did not experience any abdominal pain, vomiting or haematemesis, and now does not have any specific symptoms. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn physical examination he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Abdominal examination reveals a soft abdomen. A plain abdominal X-ray is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Observation and review","Endoscopy","Colonoscopy","CT abdomen","Laparoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this patient\u0027s X-ray, there is a normal gas pattern in the colon and the foreign body can be seen immediately to the left of the second lumbar vertebra and is almost certainly in the transverse colon (Image). Given his lack of symptoms and signs of perforation, the location of the foreign body, and the time since ingestion, there is a very high chance it will pass spontaneously and no intervention will be required, but \u003Cstrong\u003Eobservation and review\u003C/strong\u003E are necessary; particularly a psychiatric screen for self-harm and suicidality. The cynic would say that a couple of days relaxation in the comfort of a hospital bed might be an adequate stimulus and reward for a prison inmate choosing to swallow such a foreign body.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is required in high-risk presentations of foreign body ingestion. This includes patients with evidence of complete oesophageal obstruction, objects larger than 2.5cm and still in the stomach, and objects larger than 6cm in the proximal duodenum or above. Button batteries pose a risk of erosion and perforation. If swallowed and recognised, they should be retrieved wherever possible. Sharp objects only require endoscopy if they are in the proximal duodenum or above; as this is when the greatest risk for perforation is, particularly as the object passes through the pylorus.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E can be used for extremely high risk, large, foreign bodies that are in the colon, this is not the case in this patient as this foreign body will almost certainly pass without the need for intervention.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT abdomen\u003C/strong\u003E is not required as the location of the foreign body is clear in the x-ray and clinical presentation. If the object had multiple parts, was difficult to see on x-ray, or there was any doubt about its location, a CT scan may be justified.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELaparoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is reserved for patients who have signs of perforation in foreign bodies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Most foreign bodies in adults pass without any need for intervention.","High-risk foreign bodies may require endoscopy."],"references":["Ambe P, Weber SA, Schauer M, Knoefel WT. Swallowed foreign bodies in adults. Dtsch Arztebl Int. 2012;109(50):869-75. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC3536040/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74874"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1123"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15151"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15151"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab762d40-1643-4ef5-a0c7-96b82d3722e8.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ab762d40-1643-4ef5-a0c7-96b82d3722e8.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":721,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74874","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74874"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-14T15:49:26+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-14T15:49:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1123"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90775"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Su